Normal growth is limited in some cases of KTS. Even though some children might be faced with gross differences in size of the legs and feet, children with KTS don't have causes for concern as the disorder is unrelated to their intelligence.

KTS is a disorder that predominantly affects women more than men. Birth defects sometimes occur at birth or early after delivery but may also develop during pregnancy. It also causes partial obstruction of the development of the baby in the womb of the mother.

