Trisomy 7 occurs when genetic testing shows 3 chromosome copies of the number 7. It is the most commonly seen trisomy in babies, but it only occurs in 1 in 7.635 newborns, so it is not common.

Affecting males and females in equal numbers, trisomy 7 involves 7 enzyme and 2 substrate transfer pathways. It occurs when there is a fault between chromosomes. During the cells’ replication process, an error is caused by homologous chromosomes which do not separate effectively. As a result, the child is born with a higher genetic material yield than usually found.

At birth, the child will have no sign of trisomy 7 disease. The visible signs that this disease is present appear after 3 months. It usually appears in the child from the stomach area such as bloating, vomiting, weight loss. Affected children sometimes have amblyopia and hearing loss.

Other serious effects of trisomy 7 disease in children:

* miscarriage;
* epilepsy;
* underdeveloped lungs;
* poor kidney function;
* cystic fibrosis;
* cardiovascular problems;
* misaligned spine;
* nervous system problems;
* developmental disorders;
* diabetes.

In the presence of one of the above symptoms, parents need to take their children to the doctor for examination to see if there are any signs of the presence of trisomy 7 disease, then will be prescribed medicines or combated treatment method such as diet, nutrition, electrolyte replacement and drug therapy. At the same time, ensuring good psychological so that children can still learn and develop normally.
